SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 508
By Bailey
A RESOLUTION to recognize Trooper Shane Moore on the
occasion of his retirement.
WHEREAS, our nation was conceived by individuals who were willing to sacrifice their
personal concerns to ensure the public safety and welfare, and the Volunteer State is especially
proud to be the home of so many valiant individuals; and
WHEREAS, one such individual is Trooper Shane Moore of the Tennessee Highway
Patrol, who, having rendered sterling service to the people of the State of Tennessee for more
than twenty years, has taken his much-deserved retirement this year; and
WHEREAS, Trooper Shane Moore graduated from the Tennessee Highway Patrol
Academy in 2000; upon his graduation, he was assigned to Troop C of the Nashville District, in
which position he served from 2000 to 2013 and covered Montgomery, Stewart, and Houston
counties; and
WHEREAS, in 2008, Trooper Moore attended K9 training school and received a dual-
purpose dog, which was utilized in tracking people and narcotics, and in 2013, he transferred to
the K9 division within the Department of Safety to train newly assigned K9 handlers and their
partners; and
WHEREAS, Trooper Shane Moore became a part of the Capitol Protection Unit in 2019,
where he served as a handler of an explosive detector canine; during his time with the unit, he
conducted several seminars with various leadership groups, educating the public on the task
and training of explosive detector canines; and
WHEREAS, following the Christmas Day bombing in Nashville in 2020, Trooper Moore
and his K9 Sumo were one of many K9 units employed to detect any secondary devices that
